  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries around the world. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained money as legitimate income. Key components typically include:\n\n1. Requirements for financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Conduct due diligence checks\n\n2. Internationally, organizations like:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- International Monetary Fund (IMF)\n- World Bank\n\n3. In specific countries:\n- United States: Bank Secrecy Act\n- European Union: AML Directives\n- United Kingdom: Proceeds of Crime Act\n- Canada: Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act\n\nThese regulations apply to banks, credit unions, investment firms, casinos, and increasingly to cryptocurrency exchanges and other financial service providers.\n\nThe goal is to detect and prevent financial crimes like money laundering, terrorist financing, and other illegal financial activities.",
